{"title":"Level 1 — Getting Started with R","markdown":{"headingText":"Level 1 — Getting Started with R","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**Where this level is headed**\n\nYou've just started an internship, a course, or a new role that expects you to \"just use R\" for the data work — and you've never written a line of code. This level takes you from a completely blank slate to confidently running your first real analysis: computing the average age of 100 study participants from an actual survey file.\n:::\n\n## What you'll build toward\n\nEvery page in this level adds one small piece, and by the last page you'll combine all of them to solve the same running problem: **your supervisor needs the average age of the participants in a community health survey, and you need to get that number out of R.**\n\nAlong the way you'll learn what R and RStudio actually are, how to work in the console and in scripts, how R represents numbers, text, true/false values, and missing data, how to use built-in functions, how to get help when you're stuck, and how to import a real data file.\n\n## Topics in this level\n\n- What is R? What is RStudio?\n- The RStudio interface\n- Installing and loading packages\n- The Console vs. an R script\n- Comments\n- Basic arithmetic\n- The assignment operator and objects\n- Naming objects well\n- Data types: numeric, character, logical\n- Missing values (`NA`)\n- Basic functions\n- Getting help in R\n- Working directories\n- Importing your first real dataset\n\nBy the end of this level, you'll import `data/participants.csv` — a simulated community health survey — and report the mean age of its 100 participants, correctly handling the missing values hiding in it. Let's begin.\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"reti